label: Glucosamine
title: Natural Compound: A natural sugar found in shellfish shells, fungal cell walls, and the human body; a building block of cartilage that supports joint health (22)

label: Chondroitin
title: Natural Compound: A natural substance found in cartilage around joints that helps maintain cartilage structure and cushion the joints (22)

label: Gelatin
title: Natural Compound: A protein derived by boiling animal tissues, used as a gelling agent, thickener, or stabilizer in food, pharmaceutical, and industrial products, providing texture, elasticity, or encapsulation properties ()

label: Collagen
title: Natural Compound: A structural protein abundant in animal tissues such as skin, bones, and connective tissues; commercially extracted for use in gelatin production, collagen peptides, nutraceuticals, cosmetics, pharmaceuticals, and biomedical applications ()

label: Marine Collagen
title: Natural Compound: Collagen derived from marine life, most commonly fish, smaller peptide sizes than land-animal collagen, and is thought to be better absorbed by the body ()

label: MSM (Methylsulfonylmethane)
title: Natural Compound: A natural organic sulfur compound found in many living organisms, often used as a dietary supplement for potential joint and skin health benefits ()

label: Hyaluronic Acid
title: Natural Compound: A naturally occurring polysaccharide found in connective tissues and skin, known for its exceptional ability to retain moisture and support skin hydration, joint lubrication, and tissue repair ()

label: Surimi
title: Processed Food Product: Paste made from minced and rinsed Meat of mild-flavoured, lean, white Fish (most commonly Alaska Pollock and Pacific Whiting) ()

label: Excessive Fertilisation
title: Overuse of chemical fertilisers. Often relates to Agriculture

label: Industrial Waste
title: Generation of hazardous or non-recyclable waste from industry. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Plastic Pollution
title: Accumulation of plastic waste in the environment. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Energy Overconsumption
title: High use of fossil fuels or non-renewable energy. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Overfishing
title: Excessive harvesting of marine species. Often relates to Fishing

label: Habitat Destruction
title: Direct elimination of natural habitats for development. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Mining Activities
title: Extraction of minerals, including rare earths. Often relates to Energy Production

label: Urbanisation
title: Expansion of urban areas into natural landscapes. Often relates to Urban Development

label: Labour Exploitation
title: Unfair labor practices, including child labor. Often relates to Various Industries

label: IUU Fishing
title: Illegal, unreported, or unregulated fishing practices. Often relates to Fishing

label: Pesticide & Herbicide Use
title: Application of synthetic pesticides and herbicides. Often relates to Agriculture

label: Water Overuse
title: Excessive withdrawal of groundwater or surface water. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Soil Degradation
title: Loss of soil nutrients or structure due to farming practices. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Deforestation
title: Clearing of forests for agriculture or development. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Monoculture Farming
title: Cultivation of single crop species over large areas. Often relates to Agriculture

label: Greenhouse Gas (GHG) Emissions
title: Release of CO2, methane, and other GHGs from human activities. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Antibiotic Overuse
title: Excessive use of antibiotics in agriculture or medicine. Often relates to Various Industries

label: Genetic Modification
title: Use of genetically modified organisms in agriculture. Often relates to Agriculture

label: Water Contamination
title: Degradation of water quality by pollutants

label: Chemical Exposure
title: Human or wildlife contact with toxic substances

label: Antibiotic Resistance
title: Increased resistance of bacteria to antibiotics

label: Resource Scarcity
title: Depletion of natural resources like water or minerals

label: Pesticide-Resistant Pests
title: Development of pest resistance to chemical controls

label: Soil Contamination
title: Accumulation of harmful substances in soil

label: Air Pollution
title: Release of particulates or gases into the atmosphere

label: Biodiversity Loss
title: Reduction in species diversity or population

label: Ocean Acidification
title: Decrease in ocean pH due to CO2 absorption

label: Climate Change
title: Global warming and altered weather patterns

label: Soil Erosion
title: Loss of topsoil due to wind or water

label: Habitat Fragmentation
title: Division of habitats into smaller, isolated patches

label: Eutrophication
title: Nutrient overload causing algal blooms and aquatic dead zones

label: Sea Level Rise
title: Increased coastal flooding from rising oceans

label: Natural Disaster Increase
title: Higher frequency of extreme weather events

label: Social Inequality
title: Unequal access to resources or opportunities

label: Ecosystem Collapse
title: Breakdown of ecosystem structure and function

label: Public Health Crises
title: Widespread health issues from environmental factors

label: Food Insecurity
title: Lack of reliable access to sufficient food

label: Corn Farming
title: Corn/maize farming, significant global sector, high production volumes

label: Cattle Farming
title: Raising cattle for beef or dairy, incl. breeding, feeding, and herd management

label: Cattle Slaughtering
title: The Slaughtering Industry is the entry point where live Cattle are processed into carcasses and raw products for further processing

label: Dairy Farming
title: Milking and initial processing of raw milk

label: Tanning
title: Tanning and treating animal skins and hides for leather products

label: Fisheries
title: Harvesting of fish and aquatic species from wild stocks in marine and fresh water environments, including coastal, inland, and deep-sea ecosystems

label: Shark Fisheries
title: Targeted capture of sharks in marine fisheries, primarily for fins, meat, cartilage, and other derived products

label: Pig Farming
title: Breeding and raising pigs for meat production. Includes commercial and small-scale operations for pork supply

label: Pig Slaughtering
title: The Slaughtering Industry is the entry point where live Pigs are processed into carcasses and raw products for further processing

label: Livestock Trading (Bovine)
title: Import and export of live Bovines for breeding, fattening, or slaughter

label: Livestock Trading (Porcine)
title: Export and import of live Pigs for breeding or slaughter

label: Rendering (Animals)
title: Rendering Plants collect raw byproducts (e.g. bones, cartilage, hides, fat, offal, blood) from animal slaughter for processing into usable materials

label: Pharmaceuticals
title: Producing drugs, vaccines, and biologics for human and animal health

label: Pet Food
title: Manufacturing nutritional products formulated for domestic animals

label: Cosmetics
title: Creating personal care and beauty products for external human use

label: Animal Feed
title: Producing feed formulations to support livestock and poultry health and productivity

label: Fertiliser
title: Converting organic or synthetic materials into nutrient sources to enhance soil fertility and crop growth

label: Poultry Farming
title: Breeding and raising poultry (primarily chickens, turkeys, ducks) for meat or eggs

label: Livestock Trading (Poultry)
title: Import/Export of live poultry (e.g. chicks, breeding stock, or slaughter-ready birds) for breeding, fattening, or slaughter

label: Crustacean Processing
title: Preparation and handling of crustaceans for consumption, commonly shrimp, crabs, lobsters, crayfish

label: Poultry Slaughtering
title: Killing and initial processing of poultry into carcasses, primal cuts, and byproducts (e.g. feathers, offal)

label: Paper Manufacturing
title: Transforming Wood or recycled fibres into usable paper products

label: Forestry
title: The practice of managing, cultivating, and conserving forests and associated resources

label: Fish Aquaculture
title: Fish farming, breeding and raising of fish in controlled environments

label: Commercial Fishing
title: Catching fish and seafood for profit from wild fisheries in marine and freshwater environments

label: Artisanal Fishing
title: Low-tech, small-scale fishing practices by individual fishers or households, primarily for local consumption or trade

label: Crustacean Fisheries
title: Commercial harvesting of aquatic arthropods—commonly decapods such as shrimp, lobsters, and crabs

label: Biotechnology
title: Use of biological systems and organisms to develop new products and processes

label: Shrimp and Prawn Farming
title: Most heavily farmed crustaceans (e.g. Whiteleg shrimp, Giant tiger prawn, Freshwater prawn)

label: Lobster Farming
title: Commonly rock lobsters; smallest farmed share among crustaceans, minor vs wild catch (<5% of total lobster production) (36)

label: Crab Farming
title: Growing sector, though wild-caught fisheries still dominate production (1.6 mil tons wild catch vs 1.24 mil tons from aquaculture) (37)

label: Crayfish Farming
title: Growing sector within aquaculture, production volume smaller than Shrimp, Prawn, and Crab, ~200,000 metric tons (34)

label: Joint Health Supplements
title: Tablets, capsules, gummies, or powders containing Glucosamine, often combined with Chondroitin Sulfate or other compounds, used to support joint function, reduce pain, and slow cartilage degradation, commonly for osteoarthritis and joint mobility

label: Confectionery
title: Food items rich in sugar and carbohydrates

label: Capsules
title: Cylindrical enclosures—commonly made from gelatin or plant-based alternatives—used to encase and deliver medications, supplements, or other ingestible substances. Designed for easy swallowing and controlled release

label: Collagen Peptides/Hydrolysed Collagen
title: Small pieces of animal Collagen, broken down into smaller peptides or animo acids that can be absorbed through gastrointestinal tract. Commonly available in powdered, pill, or liquid forms

label: Collagen Face Cream
title: Facial skincare product containing hydrolysed Collagen, formulated to support skin elasticity, hydration, and a smoother appearance

label: Sausages
title: Processed meat products made from ground or emulsified meat, fat, and seasonings, filled into natural or synthetic casings

label: Coated Tablets
title: Solid oral dosage forms in which the compressed tablet core is covered with a polymer, sugar, or film coating to improve stability, control release, mask taste, or enhance handling in pharmaceutical manufacturing

label: Wound Dressings
title: Sterile medical materials or products applied to cover and protect wounds, designed to promote healing, control moisture, absorb exudate, and prevent contamination in clinical or surgical settings

label: Pet Supplements
title: Nutritional products formulated to support the health, growth, or specific needs of companion animals, containing vitamins, minerals, amino acids, fatty acids, or other bioactive ingredients

label: Energy Gels
title: Concentrated, easily digestible carbohydrate-based products, often with added electrolytes or other nutrients, designed to provide rapid energy for endurance activities

label: Protein Bars
title: Compact supplemental foods formulated with concentrated protein (dairy, plant, or blended), carbohydrates, fats, and added nutrients, designed for convenient nutrition and supplementation

label: Gummies
title: Soft, chewy sweets shaped in various forms, often fruit-flavored

label: Photographic Film
title: Strip of plastic coated with a chemical emultion used in analog or traditional photography

label: Crab Stick
title: Processed seafood made primarily from minced white Fish, shaped and flavoured to resemble crab meat

label: Jello
title: Wiggly, fruit-flavored dessert gel, typically served chilled

label: Marshmallows
title: Fluffy, sweet confections used in desserts or hot drinks

label: Crustacean Shells
title: Crustacean exoskeletons, often from shrimp (largest source), lobsters, crabs, and crayfish; used to produce chitin, chitosan, and glucosamine

label: Wild-Caught Fish
title: Fish harvested from natural marine and freshwater environments for food, supplements, and byproducts, incl. Cod, Tuna, Anchovies, and Sardines

label: Filamentuous Fungi
title: Saprophytic microorganisms commonly used in various industries to produce enzymes, chemicals, and other compounds

label: Bovine (Cow)
title: Domesticated cattle raised for beef, dairy, leather, and byproducts like gelatin, tallow, and bone meal

label: Sharks and Elasmobranchs
title: Cartilaginous fish harvested for meat, fins, cartilage, liver oil, and skin; byproducts used in supplements, cosmetics, and traditional medicine

label: Porcine (Pig)
title: Domesticated pigs raised for meat (pork) and byproducts such as insulin, gelatin, heparin, and lard

label: Avian (Poultry/Fowls)
title: Birds like chickens and ducks raised for meat, eggs, feathers, and byproducts such as gelatin, enzymes, and vaccines

label: Farmed Fish
title: Fish raised in controlled aquaculture systems for Food, Nutritional Supplements, and other Byproducts, most commonly Salmon, Tilapia, Catfish, and Carp

label: Dairy Cows
title: Cattle selectively bred for high milk production; central to the dairy industry for producing milk, cheese, yogurt and other dairy products

label: Lignin (Wood)
title: A complex organic polymer found in the cell walls of woody plants, providing rigidity and resistance to decay; often obtained as a byproduct of the pulp and Paper industry

label: Chitin
title: Derived from exoskeletons of arthropods and cell walls of fungi

label: Animal Skins/Hides
title: Animal hide rich in collagen, widely utilized for gelatin production, collagen peptide manufacturing, leather processing, and cosmetic or pharmaceutical formulations

label: Animal Tendons, Ligaments, and Fascia
title: Tendons, sinews, and ligaments from animals, primarily obtained as byproducts of the meat processing industry; utilized for gelatin production, collagen peptide manufacturing, nutraceuticals, and medical-grade biomaterials

label: Fish Scales & Skin
title: Collagen-rich outer tissue of fish, commercially processed for gelatin, collagen peptides, cosmetic actives, and biomedical or packaging applications such as wound dressings and biofilms

label: Other Fish Parts
title: Various fish byproducts—such as heads, bones, and fins—processed for collagen extraction, fish protein hydrolysates, animal feed, fertilizers, and biomedical uses

label: DMS (Dimethyl Sulfide)
title: A sulfur-containing compound originating from the breakdown of Lignin in wood pulp during Paper Manufacturing

label: DMSO (Dimethyl Sulfoxide)
title: A colorless, odorless organic solvent derived from the oxidation of dimethyl sulfide (DMS), used widely in industrial applications and as a precursor in the synthesis of dietary supplements like MSM

label: Rooster Combs
title: The fleshy, red, and prominent growth on top of a rooster's head, more prominent than in hens

label: Bacteria (Streptococcus spp. or Bacillus spp.)
title: Bacterial strains, typically used in fermentation for producing hyaluronic acid as well as in food processing, enzyme production, probiotics, and other industrial applications

label: Fish Meat & Products
title: Fish Flesh and related products, primarily consumed as food

label: Corn
title: Also known as maize; widely cultivated for use in food, feed, and various industrial applications

label: Animal Cartilage
title: Tough connective tissue from cattle, poultry, and fish, used for collagen/gelatin and chondroitin extraction in supplements, foods, pet feed, and biomedical applications

label: Shark Cartilage
title: Niche market, high-value material processed from shark skeletons (byproducts of meat/fin industries), mainly used in nutraceuticals and cosmetics

label: Beef (Bovine Meat)
title: Meat derived from Bovine animals, primarily Cattle, processed for human consumption and used in a wide range of food products

label: Pork (Pig Meat)
title: Meat derived from Pigs, processed for human consumption and widely used in various food products

label: Poultry (Avian Meat)
title: Meat derived from Avian species such as chicken, turkey, and duck, processed for human consumption and widely used in global food products

label: Animal Bones
title: Dense skeletal structures containing collagen and minerals; commercially rendered for gelatin, bone-derived ingredients (e.g., calcium phosphates), and functional food or pharmaceutical components
